5:
I'll have... this... and that... Ah, and a
basket of those herbs. Could you
wrap them up into five bundles
each?
8:
Wow. Looks like you already know
your way around Palpebra, huh?
12:
And to think that she could've been
a good, HONEST herbalist on that
passion alone...
16:
Good enough to be one for the
kingdom, you mean?
18:
Yeah, right. They'd have me locked
up in a cell for my deeds sooner
than later.
22: Huh? What do you mean by that?
26:
Hehe... I'm just joking. You should see
the look on your face, Alk!
32: Whoa! Sorry about that, are you hurt?
44:
I bought some food, mommy. 
With this you'll get better in a jiffy!
47:
Pardon me, but I believe you have
something of ours.
50:
I-I'm sorry! Please! If it's about the
money... I'll return it! But please,
please don't do anything to my
mommy!
56:
She's in bed all day from sickness. 
A doctor looked at her, but she still
hasn't gotten any better!
59:
Do you know any other grown-ups
who can help you?
66:
If you want to help your mother,
please step aside.
69:
This medicine... Are you the one who
bought it?
71:
No... It's what the doctor always
gave us...
76:
I can cure your mother. For a price,
of course.
80:
How could you even be talking
about money at a time like this?!
83:
What did you expect? This isn't a
charity after all.
86:
I'-I'll get you the money! It may take
some time, but I promise, I will!
90: It's a deal then. I'll start right away.
96:
You've been giving me that stare for
a while now. Are you really that
uncomfortable with how I do things?
99:
...No. I admit that your treatment is
what saved that boy's mother in the
end.
101:
But I can't say that I approve of your
methods. That's all.
105:
If it had just been me and Light, we
wouldn't have been able to treat
her. So thanks.
108:
I didn't actually give her any
treatment, you know.
112:
Wh-what do you mean? Don't tell
me you lied to her!
116:
No, no. Wasn't it obvious? The kid's
mother was never sick to begin with.
118:
She became ill from the side effects
of the wrong medicine.
120:
So stopping that allowed her to
recover all by herself.
124:
Then what was the medicine you
made for her?
128:
That was just an ordinary analeptic.
The kind that adventurers drink after
an all-nighter.
132:
That's strange... But why did the
doctor give the wrong medicine? 
It couldn't be a mistake... Or...
137:
Or the doctor might have done it…
to get money for the medicine?
140:
No doubt about it. A medicine that
potent is so obvious that it's hard to
miss unless it was on purpose.
144:
We must report this to the Guild
posthaste!
147:
That's fine with me, but would you
mind giving it one more day before
doing so?
156:
This makeshift doctor of ours. Think
about it—don't you think that this
doctor has a bit saved up?
159:
The money that he got from the
analeptic, for example. There's no
way that he's just going after pocket
change from little kids.
162:
Meaning, we should at least try and
squeeze him for what it's worth.
167:
Now wait just a second! That's
completely different from what we
were talking about!
172:
Don't even think about it, Zelma!
L-listen to me! Stop right there!
Zelma!
